edIn\"><\/a>\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments\" data-lf-site-id=\"314099\" data-lf-article-id=\"3560726\" data-url=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3560726\/a-shadow-falls-on-china\/\" data-title=\"A Shadow Falls on China\" title=\"Click to view and post comments\" data-event=\"comment-click\">0<\/a>\n        <div class=\"reprintLink\"><a href=\"https:\/\/s100.copyright.com\/AppDispatchServlet?publisherName=TIME&amp;publication=TIME&amp;title=A%20Shadow%20Falls%20on%20China&amp;publicationDate=11\/06\/2014&amp;author=Rana%20Foroohar&amp;contentID=3560726&amp;orderBeanReset=true\" data-event=\"reprints\" title=\"Click to order a reprint of this article\">Order a Reprint<\/a>\n        <\/div>\n<\/span>\n<\/aside><p>Will the next global financial crisis be manufactured in China? That&rsquo;s a question raised by the most recent report on the shadow-banking sector, from the Financial Stability Board (FSB), a group in Switzerland that coordinates the work of the world&rsquo;s financial regulators. Shadow banks are that mysterious collection of hedge funds, money-market funds and private lenders that operate outside the regulatory scrutiny of the formal banking sector. &#8230;<\/p>","section":{"name":"World","slug":"world","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/world\/","description":"The latest news and analysis from TIME's correspondents on world politics, diplomacy, conflict, culture, humanitarian disasters, religion and much more"},"tag":{"name":"Viewpoint","slug":"viewpoint","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/viewpoint\/"},"tags":"China|Curious Capitalist|Viewpoint","hero":{"class":"wide","thumbnail":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/h_12-7-00009561-1.jpg?w=100&h=100&crop=1","src":{"small":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/h_12-7-00009561-1.jpg?w=280","small_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/h_12-7-00009561-1.jpg?w=560","large":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/h_12-7-00009561-1.jpg?w=840","large_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/h_12-7-00009561-1.jpg?w=1680"},"credit":"ANJELIKA JAKOB\u2014LUZPHOTO\/REDUX ","caption":"If China\u2019s rapidly growing debt bubble bursts, it could threaten an already teetering global economy ","alt":"00009561","providers":[]},"id":3560726,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3560726%2Fa-shadow-falls-on-china%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fwp.me%2Fp5HMd-eWj4","encoded_title":"A+Shadow+Falls+on+China","twitter_text":"A%20Shadow%20Falls%20on%20China","twitter_via":"TIMEWorld","subjects":[null],"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"A Shadow Falls on China"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"Select","post_title":"A Shadow Falls on China"},"email_title":"A%20Shadow%20Falls%20on%20China%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"A%20Shadow%20Falls%20on%20China%0A%0AOff-the-books%20finance%20in%20the%20world%E2%80%99s%20second%20largest%20economy%20means%20major%20trouble%20for%20everyone%20else%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3560726%2Fa-shadow-falls-on-china%2F","icon":"key","omniture":{"modules":"rr-mag|rr-share"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3560726\/a-shadow-falls-on-china\/","widget_id":"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3554603\/next-financial-crisis\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/ti.me\/10khLhI","title":"Where the Next Financial Crisis Will Come From","friendly_title":"Where the Next Financial Crisis Will Come From","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"Where the Next Financial Crisis Will Come From","excerpt":"It won't be from the banking sector","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Nov. 3, 2014","published":"2014-11-03 13:04:50","updated":"2014-11-03 17:04:50","minute":"1:04 pm","short":"11\/3"},"authors":[{"id":209121265,"url":"https:\/\/time.com\/author\/rana-foroohar\/","name":"Rana Foroohar","bio":"Rana Foroohar is TIME's assistant managing editor in charge of economics and business.","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"RanaForoohar","twitter_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/RanaForoohar","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/03\/mg_1844_2.jpg?crop=183px%2C91px%2C2574px%2C2575px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":true}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-related\" data-name=\"rr-related\"><div class=\"read-more-inline related\"><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/8671\/why-you-need-to-worry-about-chinas-shadow-banking\/\" class=\"read-more-article\" format-article data-event=\"rr-related\"><img src=\"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/02\/china_shadow_banking_0220.jpg?w=560&#038;h=374&#038;crop=1\" alt=\"CHINA-ECONOMY\" title=\"A man walking past a ATM machine at the entrance of a bank in Beijing, Jan. 25, 2014\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><h3 class=\"read-more-inline-title\">Why You Need to Worry about China\u2019s Shadow Banking<\/h3><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p>The next financial crisis won&rsquo;t come from the banking sector. That&rsquo;s the message implicit in the latest report on the global financial sector from the Financial Stability Board, the group that monitors what&rsquo;s happening with the world&rsquo;s money flow. Instead, it&rsquo;s very likely to come from the massive and growing &ldquo;shadow banking&rdquo; sector&mdash;an area mostly untouched by our government regulators.<\/p>\n<p>New numbers show that the shadow banking industry&mdash;which includes everything from money market funds to real-estate trusts to hedge funds&mdash;grew by a whopping $5 trillion in 2013 to $75 trillion. If you look at the sector as a percentage of the global economy, that&rsquo;s nearly what is was pre-crisis, back in 2007.<\/p>\n<p>That means many of the risks that used to be held on bank balance sheets have moved to the non-regulated areas of finance. This says a number of important things. First and perhaps most importantly, all the backslapping in Washington about how much &ldquo;safer&rdquo; our banking system is now than it was six years ago is meaningless. While banks are still plenty risky, increasingly, new financial risk isn&#8217;t being held in banks &mdash; it&#8217;s being held in places that regulators can&#8217;t see it. (see <a href=\"http:\/\/business.time.com\/2013\/09\/13\/banking-system\/\" target=\"_blank\">my debate with Treasury over that fact here<\/a>.) That Dodd-Frank financial regulation wasn&rsquo;t able to do more about this is a real pity.<\/p>\n<p>One of the ways that you can already see how the shadow-banking sector is influencing the financial markets is in margin debt. That&rsquo;s a measure of the amount of debt that investors are using to buy stocks &ndash; and right now, New York Stock Exchange margin debt is at record highs; some think that&rsquo;s because hedge funds have become such huge market players, in some cases as large or larger than banks in terms of their influence. Margin debt at record highs is scary for many reasons, one of which is that when there&rsquo;s a lot of margin debt and the market turns, it speeds up a fall, leading to the kind of snowball effect that can lead to a market crash.<\/p>\n<p>While that won&rsquo;t necessarily happen any time soon, it&#8217;s worth remembering that debt itself is always the best predictor of financial crisis. As <a href=\"http:\/\/www.nber.org\/papers\/w15512\" target=\"_blank\">plenty of research shows<\/a>, over the last two hundred years or so, every single financial crisis has been preceded by a big increase in debt levels. The growth in the shadow banking sector means we now know less, not more, than we did about who&rsquo;s holding debt than before the financial crisis of 2008. That&rsquo;s something we should all be worried about.<\/p><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-ad\" data-name=\"rr-ad\"><div class=\"right-rail-ad\" id=\"right-rail-ad-3554603\"><\/div><\/aside><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-share\" data-name=\"rr-share\"><span class=\"social-links\">\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail\" href=\"mailto:?subject=Where%20the%20Next%20Financial%20Crisis%20Will%20Come%20From%20%7C%20TIME&body=Where%20the%20Next%20Financial%20Crisis%20Will%20Come%20From%0A%0AIt%20won%27t%20be%20from%20the%20banking%20sector%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3554603%2Fnext-financial-crisis%2F\" data-event=\"email\" title=\"Click to Email this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup\" href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3554603%2Fnext-financial-crisis%2F\" data-event=\"fb-share\" title=\"Click to post this article to Facebook\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup\" href=\"#\" data-href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F10khLhI&text=Where%20the%20next%20financial%20crisis%20will%20come%20from&via=TIMEBusiness\" data-event=\"tweet\" title=\"Click to Tweet this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup\" href=\"http:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3554603%2Fnext-financial-crisis%2F&title=Where+the+Next+Financial+Crisis+Will+Come+From\" data-event=\"linkedin\" title=\"Click to post this article to LinkedIn\"><\/a>\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments\" data-lf-site-id=\"314099\" data-lf-article-id=\"3554603\" data-url=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3554603\/next-financial-crisis\/\" data-title=\"Where the Next Financial Crisis Will Come From\" title=\"Click to view and post comments\" data-event=\"comment-click\">0<\/a>\n<\/span>\n<\/aside>","section":{"name":"Business","slug":"business","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/business\/","description":"The latest news and commentary from TIME on domestic and global business, the economy, technology, personal finance, banking, marketing, management and more"},"tag":{"name":"Economy","slug":"economy","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/economy\/"},"tags":"Economy","hero":{"class":"landscape","thumbnail":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/financial-crisis.jpg?w=100&h=100&crop=1","src":{"small":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/financial-crisis.jpg?w=280","small_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/financial-crisis.jpg?w=560","large":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/financial-crisis.jpg?w=550","large_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/11\/financial-crisis.jpg?w=1100"},"credit":"Mutlu Kurtbas\u2014Getty Images","caption":"","alt":"financial crisis","providers":[]},"id":3554603,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3554603%2Fnext-financial-crisis%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F10khLhI","encoded_title":"Where+the+Next+Financial+Crisis+Will+Come+From","twitter_text":"Where%20the%20next%20financial%20crisis%20will%20come%20from","twitter_via":"TIMEBusiness","related_posts":[{"id":8671,"title":"Why You Need to Worry about China\u2019s Shadow Banking","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/8671\/why-you-need-to-worry-about-chinas-shadow-banking\/","format":"article","paid":false,"edit_link":null,"contributor":false,"short_title":"Why You Need to Worry about China\u2019s Shadow Banking","hero":{"class":"landscape","thumbnail":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/02\/china_shadow_banking_0220.jpg?w=100&h=100&crop=1","src":{"small":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/02\/china_shadow_banking_0220.jpg?w=280&h=187&crop=1","small_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/02\/china_shadow_banking_0220.jpg?w=560&h=374&crop=1","large":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/02\/china_shadow_banking_0220.jpg?w=550&h=367&crop=1","large_2x":"http:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/02\/china_shadow_banking_0220.jpg?w=1100&h=734&crop=1"},"credit":"Wang Zhao \/ AFP \/ Getty Images","caption":"A man walking past a ATM machine at the entrance of a bank in Beijing, Jan. 25, 2014","alt":"CHINA-ECONOMY","providers":[]}}],"subjects":[null],"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"Where the Next Financial Crisis Will Come From"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"Select","post_title":"Where the Next Financial Crisis Will Come From"},"email_title":"Where%20the%20Next%20Financial%20Crisis%20Will%20Come%20From%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"Where%20the%20Next%20Financial%20Crisis%20Will%20Come%20From%0A%0AIt%20won%27t%20be%20from%20the%20banking%20sector%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3554603%2Fnext-financial-crisis%2F","omniture":{"modules":"rr-related|rr-ad|rr-share"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3554603\/next-financial-crisis\/","widget_id":"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3512808\/market-selloff-stocks-economy\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/ti.me\/1vhx86y","title":"What You Need to Know About the Stock Market Sell-Off","friendly_title":"What You Need to Know About the Stock Market Sell-Off","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"What You Need to Know About the Stock Market Sell-Off","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Oct. 16, 2014","published":"2014-10-16 08:09:33","updated":"2014-10-16 12:09:33","minute":"8:09 am","short":"10\/16"},"authors":[{"id":209121265,"url":"https:\/\/time.com\/author\/rana-foroohar\/","name":"Rana Foroohar","bio":"Rana Foroohar is TIME's assistant managing editor in charge of economics and business.","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"RanaForoohar","twitter_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/RanaForoohar","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/03\/mg_1844_2.jpg?crop=183px%2C91px%2C2574px%2C2575px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":true}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-outbrain\" data-name=\"rr-outbrain\"><div class=\"OUTBRAIN\" data-src=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3512808\/market-selloff-stocks-economy\/\" data-widget-id=\"SB_2\" data-ob-template=\"timemag\"><\/div><\/aside><p class=\"p1\">For the last few years, markets were from Mars, and the real economy was from Venus. The two literally occupied different worlds, as stock prices kept rising, even as wages were stagnant and growth was slow. As of yesterday, that divide has been bridged. Stock prices finally <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3512586\/business-economy-stock-markets-finance-investment\/\" target=\"_blank\">plunged<\/a> into a real correction of the kind we haven&rsquo;t seen since the apex of the European debt crisis three years ago.<\/p>\n<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-partner\" data-name=\"rr-partner\"><div class=\"read-more-list\"><h6 class=\"read-more-list-h\">More<\/h6><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3596744\/russia-economy-ukraine-sanctions-putin-geopolitical-ambition-foreign-policy\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">Russia&#8217;s Lackluster Economy Means Putin Simply Can&#8217;t Afford a New Cold War<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3590355\/un-womens-health\/\" class=\"read-more-list-article\" data-event=\"rr-more\">How Prioritizing Women&#8217;s Health Can Lift Countries Out of Poverty<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/storyline\/michael-brown-shooting\/pair-suspected-trying-acquire-bombs-ferguson-protests-n254021?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Feds Suspect Pair Sought Bombs for Ferguson Protests <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/crime-courts\/ohio-men-wrongly-convicted-murder-after-39-years-released-n253356?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">Two Ohio Men Wrongly Convicted of Murder Walk Free <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.nbcnews.com\/news\/us-news\/fsu-shooter-myron-may-left-message-i-do-not-want-n253436?cid=par-time_20141122\" class=\"read-more-partner-article\" data-event=\"rr-partner\" target=\"_blank\">FSU Shooter Left Message: 'I Do Not Want to Die in Vain' <span>NBC News<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/aside><p class=\"p1\">The question is, why now? The answer comes in two parts. First, with Europe in danger of tipping into recession, and China&rsquo;s growth much lower than the official statistics would indicate (that&rsquo;s one of the big reasons oil prices are down since China is now the world&rsquo;s major consumer of energy), investors have realized that a wimpy recovery in the U.S. isn&rsquo;t enough to buoy global growth. Sure, growth numbers were a bit better this year than last, but we&rsquo;re still in a 3 percent economy that doesn&rsquo;t look or feel much different than the 2 percent economy (see my <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3429656\/the-3-economy\/\" target=\"_blank\">Curious Capitalist column<\/a> on that topic). If you think of the global economy as three legs on a stool, the legs being the U.S., Europe, and the emerging markets led by China, what&rsquo;s becoming very clear to markets is that a 3 percent economy in the U.S. isn&rsquo;t enough to sustain global momentum. Indeed, the U.S. may grow faster than the world as a whole this year, which is an odd thing for a developed market. It speaks to how weak the global economy as a whole still is.<\/p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Second, markets have realized that this recovery has been a genetically engineered recovery. It&rsquo;s been engineered by the monetary scientists at the Fed, who&rsquo;ve pumped $4 trillion into the economy since 2009 in an attempt to strengthen an economy that is fundamentally not as strong as it looks. Despite the Fed&rsquo;s best efforts (and I agree that they needed to do something, especially in the beginning), the real economy simply hasn&rsquo;t caught up to the markets. Unemployment has ticked down, but wages still haven&rsquo;t ticked up. It&rsquo;s no accident that weak retail sales in the U.S. were one of the economic indicators that triggered the sell-off. As I&rsquo;ve said many times before, you can&rsquo;t have a sustainable recovery, one markets can really believe in, until you have the majority of the population with more money in their pockets.<\/p><div class=\"content-ad\" id=\"content-ad-3512808\"><\/div>\n<p class=\"p1\">The reality is that this hasn&rsquo;t happened in the last few years, and for many people, decades (the average male worker today makes less in real terms than he did in the early 1970s).<\/p>\n<p class=\"p1\">So does this mean we are in for a long, slow slide? Not exactly. I&rsquo;d bet more on increased volatility (if you are a subscriber, you can read this <a href=\"http:\/\/content.time.com\/time\/magazine\/article\/0,9171,2095556,00.html\" target=\"_blank\">piece I wrote<\/a> on the coming Age of Volatility, back in 2011). Markets will go up and down, but as long as the U.S. is the prettiest house on the ugly block that is the global economy, money may stay parked in the largest American multinationals longer than you&rsquo;d think. Whether or not our economy deserves the vote of confidence is another question.<\/p><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-ad\" data-name=\"rr-ad\"><div class=\"right-rail-ad\" id=\"right-rail-ad-3512808\"><\/div><\/aside><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-share\" data-name=\"rr-share\"><span class=\"social-links\">\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail\" href=\"mailto:?subject=What%20You%20Need%20to%20Know%20About%20the%20Stock%20Market%20Sell-Off%20%7C%20TIME&body=What%20You%20Need%20to%20Know%20About%20the%20Stock%20Market%20Sell-Off%0A%0A%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3512808%2Fmarket-selloff-stocks-economy%2F\" data-event=\"email\" title=\"Click to Email this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup\" href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3512808%2Fmarket-selloff-stocks-economy%2F\" data-event=\"fb-share\" title=\"Click to post this article to Facebook\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup\" href=\"#\" data-href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1vhx86y&text=What%20you%20need%20to%20know%20about%20the%20market%20sell-off&via=TIME\" data-event=\"tweet\" title=\"Click to Tweet this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup\" href=\"http:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3512808%2Fmarket-selloff-stocks-economy%2F&title=What+You+Need+to+Know+About+the+Stock+Market+Sell-Off\" data-event=\"linkedin\" title=\"Click to post this article to LinkedIn\"><\/a>\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"time-icons time-icons-comment toggle-comments\" data-lf-site-id=\"314099\" data-lf-article-id=\"3512808\" data-url=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3512808\/market-selloff-stocks-economy\/\" data-title=\"What You Need to Know About the Stock Market Sell-Off\" title=\"Click to view and post comments\" data-event=\"comment-click\">0<\/a>\n<\/span>\n<\/aside>","tag":{"name":"Economy","slug":"economy","url":"http:\/\/time.com\/tag\/economy\/"},"tags":"Economy|Markets","id":3512808,"encoded_url":"http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3512808%2Fmarket-selloff-stocks-economy%2F","encoded_shortlink":"http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1vhx86y","encoded_title":"What+You+Need+to+Know+About+the+Stock+Market+Sell-Off","twitter_text":"What%20you%20need%20to%20know%20about%20the%20market%20sell-off","twitter_via":"TIME","subjects":[null],"ads":{"neg":"false","post_title":"What You Need to Know About the Stock Market Sell-Off"},"Partner_Module":{"partner":"Select","post_title":"What You Need to Know About the Stock Market Sell-Off"},"email_title":"What%20You%20Need%20to%20Know%20About%20the%20Stock%20Market%20Sell-Off%20%7C%20TIME","email_body":"What%20You%20Need%20to%20Know%20About%20the%20Stock%20Market%20Sell-Off%0A%0A%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3512808%2Fmarket-selloff-stocks-economy%2F","omniture":{"modules":"rr-outbrain|rr-partner|rr-ad|rr-share"},"outbrain":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3512808\/market-selloff-stocks-economy\/","widget_id":"AR_6","hide":false}},{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3490118\/walmart-healthcare\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/ti.me\/1qDuKAQ","title":"Why Walmart Workers Losing Healthcare Might Not Be Bad","friendly_title":"Why Walmart Workers Losing Healthcare Might Not Be Bad","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"Why Walmart Workers Losing Healthcare Might Not Be Bad","excerpt":"Ironies abound","format":"article","time":{"pretty":"Oct. 10, 2014","published":"2014-10-10 10:58:10","updated":"2014-10-10 14:58:10","minute":"10:58 am","short":"10\/10"},"authors":[{"id":209121265,"url":"https:\/\/time.com\/author\/rana-foroohar\/","name":"Rana Foroohar","bio":"Rana Foroohar is TIME's assistant managing editor in charge of economics and business.","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"RanaForoohar","twitter_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/RanaForoohar","gplus":"","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"https:\/\/i1.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/03\/mg_1844_2.jpg?crop=183px%2C91px%2C2574px%2C2575px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":true}],"content":"<p>Talk about irony. In the same week that Walmart announced employees who work less than 30 hours will be losing their health care coverage, the company also announced that it&#8217;d be getting deeper into the business of selling insurance, making it easier for customers to price shop for insurance in stores. In some ways, this mirrors Walmart&#8217;s overall business model&mdash;keep prices down for consumers, but keep wages and benefits for employees low too.<\/p>\n<p>Ironically, under the rules of Obamacare, it&rsquo;s possible that those part time employees will get a better deal on health care exchanges, thanks to subsidies that help lower income <a href=\"http:\/\/www.vox.com\/2014\/10\/7\/6939057\/walmart-drops-insurance-good-news\" target=\"_blank\">workers buy insurance<\/a>. It&rsquo;s all part of the new landscape created by the Affordable Care Act. As Obamacare turns one year old, Joe Nocera and I discussed how it&rsquo;s changed healthcare, business, and the economy, on WNYC&rsquo;s Money Talking.<\/p>\n\t\t\t<form id=\"wpcom-iframe-form-d73215303d5bcc58dff130436cdcb10f-5470373932dc6\" target=\"wpcom-iframe-d73215303d5bcc58dff130436cdcb10f-5470373932dc6\" method=\"post\" action=\"\/\/wpcomwidgets.com\/?wpcom_origin=http%3A%2F%2Ftimedotcom.wordpress.com\" style=\"display: none\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"frameborder\" value=\"0\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"scrolling\" value=\"no\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"resize\" value=\"0\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"replace_attributes\" value=\"1\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"fallback\" value=\"&lt;p class=&quot;protected-embed-fallback&quot;&gt;This embed is invalid&lt;\/p&gt;\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"class\" value=\"\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"width\" value=\"474\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"height\" value=\"54\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"_data\" value=\"PGlmcmFtZSB3aWR0aD0iNDc0IiBoZWlnaHQ9IjU0IiBmcmFtZWJvcmRlcj0iMCIgc2Nyb2xsaW5nPSJubyIgc3JjPSIvL3d3dy53bnljLm9yZy93aWRnZXRzL29uZGVtYW5kX3BsYXllci8jZmlsZT1odHRwcyUzQSUyRiUyRmFjY291bnQud255Yy5vcmclMkZhdWRpbyUyRnhzcGYlMkY0MDUxODclMkY7Y29udGFpbmVyQ2xhc3M9d255YyI+PC9pZnJhbWU+,96ea04e190c4f73f655036b88456f6aefbfdf529\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"_tag\" value=\"protected-iframe\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<input type=\"hidden\" name=\"_hash\" value=\"d73215303d5bcc58dff130436cdcb10f\" \/>\n\t\t\t\t\t<\/form>\n\t\t\t<iframe name=\"wpcom-iframe-d73215303d5bcc58dff130436cdcb10f-5470373932dc6\" id=\"wpcom-iframe-d73215303d5bcc58dff130436cdcb10f-5470373932dc6\" width=\"474\" height=\"54\" frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\"  class=\"wpcom-protected-iframe \"><\/iframe>\n\t\t<script type=\"text\/javascript\">\n\t\t( function() {\n\t\t\tvar func 